                            'title' => '11 Bad Men’s Style “Rules” to Ignore',
                            'description' => '<p>Here are a number of supposed style rules or pieces of advice that you may have heard before that we don&rsquo;t necessarily think you need to follow all the time or in some cases at all.</p>

<p><img alt="" src="https://i.ytimg.com/vi/o9jZYFZT7Jo/hqdefault.jpg" style="height:360px; width:480px" /></p>

<p>Our primary mission here at the Gentleman&rsquo;s Gazette is to educate our audience about&nbsp;<a href="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/gentleman-what-it-means-today/" rel="noreferrer noopener" target="_blank">what it means to be a Gentleman</a>. And a big portion of that has to do with the history and traditions of classic menswear. Often when men are discussing these menswear traditions their conversation can come to be framed in terms of style rules that must be followed at all costs. While we certainly do believe that there are&nbsp;great&nbsp;many pieces of advice that are rooted in sound logic and the principles of aesthetics, thinking always in terms of ironclad rules that have to be followed is simplistic and pedantic and limits your options in terms of what you can wear stylishly. In other words, you don&rsquo;t have to think of some of these things as rules that have to be followed a hundred percent of the time and some of the things we&rsquo;re going to mention today can just be discarded altogether.</p>

<p><img alt="" src="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/Screen-Shot-2019-02-01-at-11.44.34-PM-1030x559.png" /></p>

<p>With that said, here are some supposed rules or pieces of advice that we think can be bent, broken or just left aside. These aren&rsquo;t necessarily in any particular order of importance but we&rsquo;ve numbered them today just to keep things consistent.</p>

<p><img alt="" src="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/Fit-is-important-1030x563.png" /></p>

<p>Fit is important</p>

<h2>1. Wear A Suit And Look Fantastic</h2>

<p>Advice number one, just wear a suit and you&rsquo;ll automatically look fantastic. While this piece of advice does advocate for dressing up which of course we support, it&rsquo;s a little bit too simplistic in nature. As we&rsquo;ve said countless times before in the channel,&nbsp;<a href="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/how-a-suit-should-fit/" rel="noreferrer noopener" target="_blank">fit</a>&nbsp;is the most important factor when wearing any outfit. You may have a suit that&rsquo;s constructed from the most luxurious materials available but if it doesn&rsquo;t fit your frame properly it&rsquo;s still going to look sloppy.</p>

<p><img alt="" src="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/Screen-Shot-2019-02-01-at-11.49.24-PM-1030x538.png" /></p>

<p>Quantity does not equal Quality</p>

<h2>2. More Clothes, The Better / If It&rsquo;s On Sale, Buy It</h2>

<p>Two closely related tips, the more clothes you have in your closet the better and if it&rsquo;s on sale in a store, buy it. Here&rsquo;s the thing about these two related pieces of advice. Ultimately, quantity does not equal quality. You don&rsquo;t need to have a pair of pants in every color under the sun or a jacket for each day of the month in your closet. There&rsquo;s nothing wrong with having options, of course, but having a modestly sized closet full of garments that you wear regularly and that look good on you will ultimately serve you just as well if not better than having an excess of options. This dovetails into another tip don&rsquo;t buy something you&rsquo;re not going to wear. Even if you see a deal in a store and it&rsquo;s 90% off, if you don&rsquo;t think the garment in question is one that&rsquo;s going to look good on you or one that won&rsquo;t harmonize with other pieces in your wardrobe, don&rsquo;t buy it. Save your money however small the amount may be for something that you will wear regularly.</p>

<h2>3. Expensive = High Quality / Buy Only Name Brand Items</h2>

<p>Another two closely related tips, if something is expensive it must be of high quality and you should only buy name-brand items. These are sort of the reverse of the tip about items being on sale. Just because something is very expensive or has a brand name associated with it doesn&rsquo;t necessarily mean that it&rsquo;s high quality. Oftentimes you&rsquo;re really just going to be paying the extra money for the brand name itself. Whenever you&rsquo;re buying any garment your primary focus should be on the quality of construction, the materials used and whether that garment in question will work well with other pieces in your wardrobe.</p>

<p><img alt="" src="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/Follow-the-trend-1030x531.png" /></p>

<p>Trends are trends for a reason</p>

<h2>4. Follow The Current Trends</h2>

<p>An easy way to get started with dressing better is to follow some of the current trends that are going on. It&rsquo;s never a bad thing to want to upgrade your personal style unless you&rsquo;re just doing it for superficial reasons or to fish for compliments. If you go out and buy a bunch of items of clothing that are trendy at the moment chances are that they&rsquo;re probably going to be out of fashion in a year or maybe even less time. After all, trends are trends for a reason. Instead just invest in quality garments that follow these solid principles of aesthetics: fit, function,&nbsp;<a href="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/how-to-use-the-color-wheel-to-assemble-superior-outfits/" rel="noreferrer noopener" target="_blank">color theory</a>&nbsp;and so on. If you do this, people&rsquo;s compliments about your improving style will be genuine as will their respect.</p>

<h2>5. Outfits Should Match / Black And Brown Don&rsquo;t Go Together</h2>

<p>A general tip and a more specific tip, everything in your outfit should match and more specifically that you can&rsquo;t wear black and brown together. People often advocate for a monochromatic look because it&rsquo;s a relatively safe way of looking put together after all you won&rsquo;t have any wildly clashing colors if you&rsquo;re wearing all the same color. Similarly, people say that black and brown are too fundamentally different in terms of formality to be paired together both of these tips require a bit more nuance to be helpful.</p>

<p>First of all, not every article of clothing in your outfit has to match exactly. The thing you should be shooting for is for all of your garments to harmonize in a way that&rsquo;s aesthetically pleasing. For example, you could be wearing an all-black outfit but keep in mind that there are subtle variations in shades of black between different garments of different fabrics and with different dyes and so on. And if some of these&nbsp;<a href="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/the-most-overrated-color-black/" rel="noreferrer noopener" target="_blank">blacks</a>&nbsp;in your clothes are looking almost the same but not quite this can be jarring to the eye. And it might have been a better decision to wear something in different colors that harmonized well. Similarly, black and brown can absolutely be worn together if the garments in question harmonize in terms of intensity and&nbsp;<a href="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/the-formality-scale-how/" rel="noreferrer noopener" target="_blank">formality</a>.</p>

