<p>In a nutshell, a notched lapel is less formal than a peak lapel, which is the most formal kind, appearing on power suits and formal wear. On a tuxedo or dinner jacket, you may also see a shawl collar; this is limited to formal jackets, so it remains more elevated than a notch lapel but is still more relaxed than a peak lapel. Thus, for example, a white dinner jacket that would be worn on a summer&nbsp;<a href="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/cruise-ship-primer/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" title="Cruise Ship Primer">cruise</a>&nbsp;should technically have a shawl collar given the relatively relaxed nature of the garment compared to a black tuxedo.</p>

<p><a href="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/tom-ford.jpg"><img alt="Tom Ford in a double-breasted tuxedo with peak lapels and jetted pockets." src="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/tom-ford.jpg" /></a></p>

