<h2>4.&nbsp;&nbsp;Esquire Encyclopedia Of 20th-Century Men&rsquo;s Fashion &ndash; O. E. Schoeffler</h2>

<p>That&rsquo;s quite a mouthful and even though it&rsquo;s so old, it&rsquo;s such a good book because it&rsquo;s very comprehensive and it&rsquo;s over 600 pages. Just look at the table of contents, it doesn&rsquo;t just talk about formal evening wear but also formal day wear and there is a chapter on&nbsp;<a href="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/vest-waistcoat-guide/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" title="Vest &amp; Waistcoat Guide">waistcoats</a>,&nbsp;<a href="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/shop/evening-wear-tuxedo-black-tie-white-tie/cummerbunds" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" title="">cummerbunds</a>, and other clothing. It&rsquo;s a fantastic book that has lots of illustrations as well as a glossary and a dictionary that really help you to find things quickly if you don&rsquo;t know what certain terminology means.</p>

<p>That aside, it&rsquo;s usually something you leave in your&nbsp;<a href="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/coffee-table-books-for-gentlemen/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" title="Coffee Table Books for Gentlemen">coffee table</a>&nbsp;and read on a cold day in front of the fire. Sadly, this book is out of print and you can sometimes find it at libraries but more often than not, they sold it years ago. Because it&rsquo;s out of print, it often goes north of $1,000 per copy sometimes you&rsquo;re lucky and you may end up getting it for 100 or $200 so be patient and when the opportunity arises, definitely get a copy.</p>

