                            'title' => 'What Is a Signet Ring & How to Wear Them Like A Gentleman',
                            'description' => '<p>For thousands of years, men of influence have been donning a wearable form of identification and communication known as the signet ring. Today, it&rsquo;s simply an attractive accessory that any man can wear. We&rsquo;ll explore how.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h2>What is a Signet Ring?</h2>

<p>Have you ever wondered why some men wear engraved rings on their ring or pinky finger? It is a signet ring. Signet rings have been a practical part of men&rsquo;s fashion for thousands of years. For wealthy and important men, a signet ring was a powerful tool akin to a signature. A signet ring is set apart from other rings based on an engraved or raised symbol, series of words or letters, or image on the top half of the ring that was representative of its wearer in some way. It could have been a name, initials, job title, rank, organization or family crest.</p>

<p>Though no longer necessary to seal correspondence, it was once an essential part of society and culture and played a significant role in history. We&rsquo;ll explore the rich history of the signet ring, how to wear it, and where and how to buy one. Considered the &ldquo;gentleman&rsquo;s ring&rdquo;, we hope you enjoy this primer.</p>

<p><img alt="" src="https://i.ytimg.com/vi/YmYMjd1NDI4/hqdefault.jpg" style="height:360px; width:480px" /></p>

<p><a href="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/mens-ring-survey/" target="_blank">Want a signet ring without breaking the bank? Click here</a></p>

<h2>The History of Signet Rings</h2>

<p><a href="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/Joachim-von-Anhalt-with-signet-ring-on-index-finger-of-left-hand.jpg"><img alt="Joachim von Anhalt with signet ring on index finger of left hand" src="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/Joachim-von-Anhalt-with-signet-ring-on-index-finger-of-left-hand-725x1030.jpg" /></a></p>

<p>Nobility were the original wearers of signet rings, such as Prince Joachim von Anhalt, painted in 1532 wearing a signet ring on the index finger of his left hand that shows the Anhalt coat of arms</p>

<p>Historically, signet rings played a significant role in business and politics. Used as a seal, a&nbsp;<a href="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/gentleman-what-it-means-today/" rel="noopener" title="What It Means To Be A Gentleman Today">gentleman</a>&nbsp;would use his ring featuring his unique family crest, emblem or monogram to stamp important documents. By dipping the ring into hot wax or soft clay, the ring left a distinct seal that was considered, at the time, to be more official than that of a signature.</p>

<p>Used on a global scale by the world&rsquo;s leaders and monumental men, the ring was seen as a way to prove authenticity. They are often referred to as seal rings today.</p>

<p><img alt="The signet ring is used as a seal for wax" src="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Signet-ring-used-as-a-seal-1030x1030.jpg" /></p>

<p>The signet ring is used as a seal for wax</p>

<p>The ring itself had markings on it that identified the specific person or the family of the person wearing it. Sometimes this was a family crest or a coat of arms, but other times it was nothing more than an icon or a monogram that was associated with a family.</p>

<p><img alt="A signet ring bearing an inversely-inscribed family crest" src="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Family-Crest-Seal-1.jpg" /></p>

<p>A signet ring bearing an inversely-inscribed family crest</p>

<p>The ring was made in mirrored image to ensure it came out properly when leaving its mark or impression. Therefore, the rings are often difficult to make and cost a significant amount of money.</p>

<p><img alt="Mesopotamian Signet Ring" src="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Mesopatamian-Signet-Ring-1030x1030.jpg" /></p>

<p>Mesopotamian Signet Ring</p>

<p>Signet rings have been used since as far back as 3500 BC when the people of Mesopotamia began using them as a method of authenticity. Initially, a seal as opposed to a ring, it was a cylindrical device that was rolled across wet clay leaving a distinct impression in the clay. Used to seal a variety of envelopes, jars, and packages, they also functioned in the same way as corporate seals do today, and of course, this is where the corporate seal comes from.</p>

<p><img alt="Ancient Mesopotamian Rolling Seal Ring" src="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Ancient-Mesopatamian-Rolling-Seal-Ring-1030x1030.jpg" /></p>

<p>Ancient Mesopotamian Rolling Seal Ring</p>

<p>In Ancient Egypt, pharaohs, religious leaders, and nobles would wear the rings made of stone or pottery called faience. The rings were flat on the outside and ornate with decorations and symbols used to denote its owner.</p>

<p><img alt="An ancient Egyptian faience ring for Tutankhamen from 1332 BC" src="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/1332-BC-Egyptian-Faience-Ring-for-Tutankhamun.jpg" /></p>

<p>An ancient Egyptian faience ring for Tutankhamen from 1332 BC</p>

<p>In fact, the Old Testament even mentions signet rings in the story of Daniel in the lion&rsquo;s den&hellip;</p>

<blockquote>
<p>And a stone was brought, and laid upon the mouth of the den; and the king sealed it with his own signet, and with the signet of his lords; that the purpose might not be changed concerning Daniel. (Daniel 6:17)</p>
</blockquote>

<p>In the Early Minoan age, the rings were formed out of soft stones and ivory. Come the Middle Minoan age they were made of harder stone, and by the Late Bronze age, they had become the signet rings we would recognize today. During the Hellenistic period (323 BC &ndash; 31 AD), they were considered an art form in addition to being used for a purpose. Around the same time. King Mithridates VI of Pontus was an avid collector of signet rings.</p>

<p><img alt="This Roman military ring was likely award to a veteran soldier of Legio XI Claudia who fought on behalf of Emperor Gallienus in the mid-3rd century AD" src="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Roman-Military-Ring-circa-3rd-Century-AD.jpg" /></p>

<p>This Roman military ring was likely award to a veteran soldier of Legio XI Claudia who fought on behalf of Emperor Gallienus in the mid-3rd century AD</p>

<p>By medieval times, most members of the nobility wore a signet ring and used it to sign and seal their letters of nobility or other important papers. The signet ring was now widely considered the only authentic way to sign without concern of forgery or tampering.</p>

<p><img alt="Byzantine Signet Ring from the 6th century" src="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Byzantine-Signet-Ring-993x1030.jpg" /></p>

<p>Byzantine Signet Ring from the 6th century</p>

<p>By the fourteenth century and under the stronghold or King Edward II, it was said that all official documents must bear the seal of the king&rsquo;s signet ring.</p>

<p><a href="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/Hexagonal-Gold-Signet-Ring-of-Michael-Zorianos.jpg"><img alt="Hexagonal Gold Signet Ring of Michael Zorianos" src="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/Hexagonal-Gold-Signet-Ring-of-Michael-Zorianos-1030x762.jpg" /></a></p>

<p>Hexagonal Gold Signet Ring of Michael Zorianos, circa 1300 AD; the inscription reads &ldquo;seal of Michael Zorianos&rdquo; in reverse</p>

<p>Despite some people having signet rings that were handed down, most of them are quite modern. For many centuries, the ring would be destroyed when the owner passed, and because they were worn by noblemen, they weren&rsquo;t copied and were considered very valuable, hence their name &ldquo;signet&rdquo; which is translated to mean &ldquo;a small seal employed for formal or official purpose&rdquo;.</p>

<p><a href="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/Hans-Holbein-the-Younger-Sir-Thomas-More-Signet-Ring-on-Index-Finger-of-Left-Hand.jpg"><img alt="A portrait of Sir Thomas More by Hans Holbein showing the subject\'s Signet Ring on his index finger of his left hand" src="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/Hans-Holbein-the-Younger-Sir-Thomas-More-Signet-Ring-on-Index-Finger-of-Left-Hand-828x1030.jpg" /></a></p>

<p>A portrait of Sir Thomas More by Hans Holbein showing the subject&rsquo;s Signet Ring on his index finger of his left hand</p>

<p>By the middle ages and well into the nineteenth century, most men wore these rings with some form of a badge on the flat side. With the King&rsquo;s signet being the most prized signet in the world, all men viewed their rings as important artifacts. It was a mark of elitism, class and that you were a member of the superior society of men if you had a true signet ring.</p>

<p>Despite legal documents being around, the art of handwriting was not and that&rsquo;s one reason why the signet ring was so vital and important to members of society who would be responsible for signing such documents. Since the ring was so powerful, it was sometimes destroyed when the man died and often a ceremony or ritual was performed.</p>

<p><a href="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/Portrait-of-a-Man-with-a-Moors-Head-on-His-Signet-Ring.jpg"><img alt="Portrait of a Man with a Moors Head on His Signet Ring" src="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/Portrait-of-a-Man-with-a-Moors-Head-on-His-Signet-Ring-710x1030.jpg" /></a></p>

<p>Portrait of a Man with a Moors Head on His Signet Ring</p>

<p>The first signet rings were made with raised decoration and lettering whereas, following the development of sealing wax, it was actually made with a depressed design.</p>

<p>The image would be left when the ring was pressed into it, therefore, had to be resilient to wear and damage. Often the rings would be made of gold or silver with the design cast, rather than carved into the flat end of the ring.</p>

<p><img alt="Rebus Signet Ring" src="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/Rebus-Signet-Ring-900x636.webp" /></p>

<p>Rebus Signet Ring</p>

<p>Although large in size, they were also intended as a symbol of class and wealth. Due to the considerable cost, many families had a single ring that was handed down from father to son &ndash; only the very wealthy or important members of society had rings exclusive to them. This included the king, religious leaders, doctors of medicine, barristers and solicitors as well as other noblemen.</p>

<p>With the popularity of the rings increasing, many families would keep these heavy and large rings in family jewel boxes as they became more ornate and decorated over the years. Many times men would opt not to wear them on their finger and instead mounted them on chains or the fob of their pocket watch.</p>

<p><img alt="Victorian signet fob collection" src="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Victorian-signet-fob-collection-1030x529.jpg" /></p>

<p>Victorian signet fob collection</p>

<p>The most common rings were initials and monograms with the more titled men wearing rings decorated with their official coat of arms or family crest. Some had simple symbols and others had one letter or a distinct pattern.</p>

