                        'description' => '<p>Contemporary sartorial authorities&nbsp;typically&nbsp;refer to just two options for formal silk:&nbsp;<a href="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/shop/evening-wear-tuxedo-black-tie-white-tie/black-tie-bow-ties">satin or ribbed (aka grosgrain)</a>.&nbsp;So when I recently came across a historical reference to a third option &ndash; &ldquo;dull silk&rdquo; &ndash; it was&nbsp;an eye-opener in&nbsp;a couple of ways.</p>

<p><img alt="" src="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Catoir-Grosgrain-ad-from-1933-Illustration-by-Robert-Goodman-777x1030.jpg" /></p>

<h2>Silk Satin</h2>

<p>Firstly, it explained the dichotomy of&nbsp;Victorian and Edwardian&nbsp;sources referring&nbsp;to facings as being &ldquo;silk or satin&rdquo; as if the two were somehow mutually exclusive. &nbsp;In actual fact,&nbsp;satin is a finish that can be produced by&nbsp;numerous&nbsp;materials, including silk. &nbsp;Although some modern sources define satin solely as a synthetic version of silk, that is not only incorrect (likely stemming from the fact that most satin textiles these days are indeed cheaper synthetics, ) but it obviously couldn&rsquo;t apply to facings made prior&nbsp;to the 1940s as polyester had not yet been invented. &nbsp;This had me scratching my head for many years until I came across the aforesaid&nbsp;reference&nbsp;in&nbsp;a 1936 fashion magazine:</p>

<p>Lapels of&nbsp;<a href="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/tuxedo-black-tie-guide/classic/tuxedo-dinner-suit/" rel="noopener" target="_blank" title="Classic Tuxedo">single-breasted dinner jackets</a>&nbsp;are usually faced with dull silk, grosgrain or barathea. &nbsp;With the more informal double-breasted&nbsp;<a href="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/dinner-jacket-black-tie-guide/" rel="noopener" target="_blank" title="Dinner Jacket Black Tie Guide">dinner jacket,</a>&nbsp;many men have the shawl collar faced with satin.</p>

<p><img alt="This midnight blue jacket features lapels faced in black grosgrain silk." src="https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/Midnight-Blue-Tuxedo-Jacket-Black-Lapels-1030x687.jpg" /></p>

<p>This midnight blue jacket features lapels faced in black grosgrain silk.</p>

<h2>Dull Silk &ndash; A Forgotten Tuxedo Lapel Material</h2>

<p>The passage suggested to me that early authorities used&nbsp;the term &lsquo;silk&rsquo; as shorthand for &lsquo;dull silk&rsquo;. &nbsp;I searched&nbsp;my archives for similar references&nbsp;and found this&nbsp;caption&nbsp;in a 1940 issue of&nbsp;<em>Esquire</em>: &ldquo;the new satin shawl collar and more conventional dull silk peak lapel&rdquo;. The classification&nbsp;of dull silk as&nbsp;&ldquo;conventional&rdquo;&nbsp;certainly re-enforces my theory&nbsp;that &lsquo;dull&rsquo;&nbsp;was implied&nbsp;in early references to &lsquo;silk&rsquo; facings. The second revelation was that&nbsp;&lsquo;satin&rsquo; is a fairly fluid term today, kind of like &ldquo;midnight blue&rdquo;. &nbsp;The facings on my various tuxedos might or might not qualify&nbsp;as satin (see the very technical description&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Satin" rel="noopener" target="_blank">here</a>) but they are a far cry from the high-gloss appearance I associate with that term. &nbsp;I would more accurately describe them as being dull silk because even though it has no fixed definition the term much more accurately captures&nbsp;their low-lustre finish.</p>

